Good Morning Fargo! We’re here in North Dakota for the @fargoairsho and this is a very special weekend for us! This is the hometown of our very own Cmdr. Brian Kesselring, commanding officer and flight leader of the Blue Angels! Cmdr. Kesselring graduated from Fargo South High School in 1995, and then went on to graduate from Concordia College in 2000. The entire team is honored to represent the Navy and Marine Corps in Cmdr. Kesselring’s hometown. Come out and see us this weekend July 24-25th at the Hector International Airport!

#BlueAngels #USNavy #USMC #FlyNavy

node.text:
This morning we had the honor and privilege to visit the @uss_constitution and the city of #Boston during our transit flight to Brunswick, Maine. Thank you to everyone who came out and watched us fly through your amazing city.

“At first glance, our 19th-century, wooden frigate and the tactical fighter pilots of the Blue Angels could not be more different; however, our two units are the same in that we both represent the highest standards of naval excellence and serve a shared mission of inspiring pride in the professionalism and service of the men and women of the U.S. Navy and Marine Corps,” said Cmdr. John Benda, USS Constitution’s 76th commanding officer.

#USNavy #OldIronsides #FlyNavy

node.text:
Good afternoon #BlueAngels fans! Each year we have the unique opportunity to pair-up with a boot camp division at the Recruit Training Command in Great Lakes, IL to provide support, encouragement, and mentorship for Navy recruits. 

This year, the Blue Angels sponsored Division 365 during their basic training cycle from July to August 2021. Providing motivation and mentorship, team members were present for some of 365’s significant milestones throughout the 8-week training experience, including their final Physical Fitness Assessment, Battlestations-21, and Pass-in-Review. 

For their final week, our Command Master Chief, CMDCM Eric McDermott got a chance to speak to the recruits and attend their graduation! What an awesome experience. Welcome to the fleet, shipmates!

@rtcgreatlakes #RecruitTrainingCommand #USNavy #ItStartsHere #BootCamp

node.text:
“Being a part of this Blue Angel family has been the greatest honor of my career. It has taught me the true meaning of teamwork and opened my eyes on what people can accomplish when they are all there to support each other.” - Aviation Structural Mechanic (Safety Equipment) Petty Officer 1st Class A.J. Acosta Jr., San Angelo, Texas

Acosta is a member of the Blue Angels’ Life Support department. The Life Support work center comprises Navy Aviation Structural Mechanics - Safety Equipment technicians and Aircrew Survival Equipment technicians. They maintain and repair the systems that support the life of the pilot in normal and emergency situations. These systems include air conditioning, avionics cooling, heating, canopy and ejection seat emergency escape systems, and more. They also maintain the personal flight gear the pilots must wear, such as helmets, oxygen masks, inflatable flotation devices, and ejection seat flight harnesses.

Additional photos are from Acosta's time serving with VFA 102 Diamondbacks.

@usnavy @marines #MaintainerMonday #USNavy #AirShow

“I went to my first Blue Angels show at 2 weeks old, now I am a part of the same team..” 

-Aviation Structural Mechanic 1st Class Sam Smith, Virginia Beach, Virginia.

The Airframes work center is responsible for maintaining flight controls; hydraulic systems; landing, arresting and catapult gear; and performs composite and sheet metal structural repairs on the F/A-18 Super Hornet.

Additional photos are from Smith’s time as a SERE (Survival, Evasion, Resistance, and Escape) Instructor, and while serving with VFA 83 aboard USS Dwight D. Eisenhower (CVN 69).
